
[1]glaze

   GLAZE, v.t. [from glass.] To furnish with windows of glass; as, to
   glaze a house.

   1. To incrust with a vitreous substance, the basis of which is lead,
   but combined with silex, pearl-ashes and common salt; as, to glaze
   earthen ware.

   2. To cover with any thing smooth and shining; or to render the
   exterior of a thing smooth, bright and showy.

   Though with other ornaments he may glaze and brandish the weapons.

   3. To give a glass surface; to make glossy; as, to glaze cloth.
